# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artifact-signing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] A **checksum** is a small-sized block of data derived from another block of digital data for the purpose of detecting errors that may have been introduced during its transmission or storage.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] By themselves, checksums are often used to verify data integrity but are not relied upon to verify data authenticity.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The procedure which generates this checksum is called a **checksum function** or **checksum algorithm**.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] Depending on its design goals, a good checksum algorithm usually outputs a significantly different value, even for small changes made to the input.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] Checksum functions are related to hash functions, fingerprints, randomization functions, and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] However, each of those concepts has different applications and therefore different design goals.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] For instance, a function returning the start of a string can provide a hash appropriate for some applications but will never be a suitable checksum.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] Checksums are used as cryptographic primitives in larger authentication algorithms.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] For cryptographic systems with these two specific design goals, see HMAC.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] Check digits and parity bits are special cases of checksums, appropriate for small blocks of data (such as Social Security numbers, bank account numbers, computer words, single bytes, etc.).
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] Some error-correcting codes are based on special checksums which not only detect common errors but also allow the original data to be recovered in certain cases.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The simplest checksum algorithm is the so-called longitudinal parity check, which breaks the data into "words" with a fixed number *n* of bits, and then computes the bitwise exclusive or (XOR) of all those words.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The result is appended to the message as an extra word.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] In simpler terms, for *n*=1 this means adding a bit to the end of the data bits to guarantee that there is an even number of '1's.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] To check the integrity of a message, the receiver computes the bitwise exclusive or of all its words, including the checksum; if the result is not a word consisting of *n* zeros, the receiver knows a transmission error occurred.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] With this checksum, any transmission error which flips a single bit of the message, or an odd number of bits, will be detected as an incorrect checksum.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] However, an error that affects two bits will not be detected if those bits lie at the same position in two distinct words.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] Also swapping of two or more words will not be detected.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] If the affected bits are independently chosen at random, the probability of a two-bit error being undetected is 1/*n*.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] A variant of the previous algorithm is to add all the "words" as unsigned binary numbers, discarding any overflow bits, and append the two's complement of the total as the checksum.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] To validate a message, the receiver adds all the words in the same manner, including the checksum; if the result is not a word full of zeros, an error must have occurred.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] This variant, too, detects any single-bit error, but the pro modular sum is used in SAE J1708.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The simple checksums described above fail to detect some common errors which affect many bits at once, such as changing the order of data words, or inserting or deleting words with all bits set to zero.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The checksum algorithms most used in practice, such as Fletcher's checksum, Adler-32, and cyclic redundancy checks (CRCs), address these weaknesses by considering not only the value of each word but also its position in the sequence.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] This feature generally increases the cost of computing the checksum.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The idea of fuzzy checksum was developed for detection of email spam by building up cooperative databases from multiple ISPs of email suspected to be spam.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The content of such spam may often vary in its details, which would render normal checksumming ineffective.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] By contrast, a "fuzzy checksum" reduces the body text to its characteristic minimum, then generates a checksum in the usual manner.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] This greatly increases the chances of slightly different spam emails producing the same checksum.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The ISP spam detection software, such as SpamAssassin, of co-operating ISPs, submits checksums of all emails to the centralised service such as DCC.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] If the count of a submitted fuzzy checksum exceeds a certain threshold, the database notes that this probably indicates spam.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] ISP service users similarly generate a fuzzy checksum on each of their emails and request the service for a spam likelihood.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] A message that is *m* bits long can be viewed as a corner of the *m*-dimensional hypercube.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The effect of a checksum algorithm that yields an *n*-bit checksum is to map each *m*-bit message to a corner of a larger hypercube, with dimension *m* + *n*.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The 2*m* + *n* corners of this hypercube represent all possible received messages.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The valid received messages (those that have the correct checksum) comprise a smaller set, with only 2*m* corners.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] A single-bit transmission error then corresponds to a displacement from a valid corner (the correct message and checksum) to one of the *m* adjacent corners.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] An error which affects *k* bits moves the message to a corner which is *k* steps removed from its correct corner.
[src:artifact-signing/checksum] The goal of a good checksum algorithm is to spread the valid corners as far from each other as possible, to increase the likelihood "typical" transmission errors will end up in an invalid corner.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Code signing can provide several valuable features.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The most common use of code signing is to provide security when deploying; in some programming languages, it can also be used to help prevent namespace conflicts.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Almost every code signing implementation will provide some sort of digital signature mechanism to verify the identity of the author or build system, and a checksum to verify that the object has not been modified.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] It can also be used to provide versioning information about an object or to store other metadata about an object.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The efficacy of code signing as an authentication mechanism for software depends on the security of underpinning signing keys.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] As with other public key infrastructure (PKI) technologies, the integrity of the system relies on publishers securing their private keys against unauthorized access.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Keys stored in software on general-purpose computers are susceptible to compromise.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Therefore, it is more secure, and best practice, to store keys in secure, tamper-proof, cryptographic hardware devices known as hardware security modules or HSMs.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Many code signing implementations will provide a way to sign the code using a system involving a pair of keys, one public and one private, similar to the process employed by TLS or SSH.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] For example, in the case of .NET, the developer uses a private key to sign their libraries or executables each time they build.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] This key will be unique to a developer or group or sometimes per application or object.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The developer can either generate this key on their own or obtain one from a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Code signing is particularly valuable in distributed environments, where the source of a given piece of code may not be immediately evident - for example Java applets, ActiveX controls and other active web and browser scripting code.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Another important usage is to safely provide updates and patches to existing software.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Windows, Mac OS X, and most Linux distributions provide updates using code signing to ensure that it is not possible for others to maliciously distribute code via the patch system.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] It allows the receiving operating system to verify that the update is legitimate, even if the update was delivered by third parties or physical media (disks).
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Code signing is used on Windows and Mac OS X to authenticate software on first run, ensuring that the software has not been maliciously tampered with by a third-party distributor or download site.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Debian-based Linux distributions (among others) validate downloaded packages using public key cryptography.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The public key used to authenticate the code signature should be traceable back to a trusted root authority CA, preferably using a secure public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] This does not ensure that the code itself can be trusted, only that it comes from the stated source (or more explicitly, from a particular private key).
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] A CA provides a root trust level and is able to assign trust to others by proxy.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] If a user trusts a CA, then the user can presumably trust the legitimacy of code that is signed with a key generated by that CA or one of its proxies.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Many operating systems and frameworks contain built-in trust for one or more certification authorities.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] It is also commonplace for large organizations to implement a private CA, internal to the organization, which provides the same features as public CAs, but it is only trusted within the organization.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Extended validation (EV) code signing certificates are subject to additional validation and technical requirements.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] These guidelines are based on the CA/B Forum's Baseline Requirements and Extended Validation Guidelines.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Certain applications, such as signing Windows 10 kernel-mode drivers, require an EV code signing certificate.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] This is an example of a decoded EV code signing certificate used by SSL.com to sign software.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] `SSL.com EV Code Signing Intermediate CA RSA R3` is shown as the Issuer's commonName, identifying this as an EV code signing certificate.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The certificate's `Subject` field describes SSL Corp as an organization.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] `Code Signing` is shown as the sole X509v3 Extended Key Usage.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The other model is the trust on first use model, in which developers can choose to provide their own self-generated key.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] In this scenario, the user would normally have to obtain the public key in some fashion directly from the developer to verify the object is from them for the first time.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Many code signing systems will store the public key inside the signature.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Some software frameworks and OSs that check the code's signature before executing will allow you to choose to trust that developer from that point on after the first run.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] An application developer can provide a similar system by including the public keys with the installer.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The key can then be used to ensure that any subsequent objects that need to run, such as upgrades, plugins, or another application, are all verified as coming from that same developer.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Time-stamping was designed to circumvent the trust warning that will appear in the case of an expired certificate.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] In effect, time-stamping extends the code trust beyond the validity period of a certificate.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] In the event that a certificate has to be revoked due to a compromise, a specific date and time of the compromising event will become part of the revocation record.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] In this case, time-stamping helps establish whether the code was signed before or after the certificate was compromised.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Developers need to sign their iOS and tvOS apps before running them on any real device and before uploading them to the App Store.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] This is needed to prove that the developer owns a valid Apple Developer ID.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] An application needs a valid profile or certificate so that it can run on the devices.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Like any security measure, code signing can be defeated.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Users can be tricked into running unsigned code, or even into running code that refuses to validate, and the system only remains secure as long as the private key remains private.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] It is also important to note that code signing does not protect the end user from any malicious activity or unintentional software bugs by the software author — it merely ensures that the software has not been modified by anyone other than the author.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Sometimes, sandbox systems do not accept certificates, because of a false time-stamp or because of an excess usage of RAM.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Microsoft implements a form of code signing (based on Authenticode) provided for Microsoft tested drivers.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Since drivers run in the kernel, they can destabilize the system or open the system to security holes.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] For this reason, Microsoft tests drivers submitted to its WHQL program.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] After the driver has passed, Microsoft signs that version of the driver as being safe.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] On 32-bit systems only, installing drivers that are not validated with Microsoft is possible after agreeing to allow the installation at a prompt warning the user that the code is unsigned.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] For .NET (managed) code, there is an additional mechanism called Strong Name Signing that uses Public/Private keys and SHA-1 hash as opposed to certificates.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] However, Microsoft discourages reliance on Strong Name Signing as a replacement for Authenticode.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] The CAs subsequently issued announcements on compliance with the decision.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] In the context of consumer devices such as games consoles, the term "unsigned code" is often used to refer to an application which has not been signed with the cryptographic key normally required for software to be accepted and executed.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] Most console games have to be signed with a secret key designed by the console maker or the game will not load on the console (both to enforce Vendor lock-in and combat software piracy).
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] There are several methods to get unsigned code to execute which include software exploits, the use of a modchip, a technique known as the swap trick or running a softmod.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] It may not initially seem obvious why simply copying a signed application onto another DVD does not allow it to boot.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] On the Xbox, the reason for this is that the Xbox executable file (XBE) contains a media-type flag, which specifies the type of media that the XBE is bootable from.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] On nearly all Xbox software, this is set such that the executable will only boot from factory-produced discs, so simply copying the executable to burnable media is enough to stop the execution of the software.
[src:artifact-signing/code-signing] However, since the executable is signed, simply changing the value of the flag is not possible as this alters the signature of the executable, causing it to fail validation when checked.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:artifact-signing/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:artifact-signing/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] November 2023 saw two drafts aiming to update the 2007 OpenPGP v4 specification (RFC4880), ultimately resulting in the RFC 9580 standard in July 2024.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The proposal from the GnuPG developers, which is called LibrePGP, was not taken up by the OpenPGP Working Group and future versions of GnuPG will not support the current version of OpenPGP.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG is part of the GNU Project and received major funding from the German government in 1999.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG is a hybrid-encryption software program because it uses a combination of conventional symmetric-key cryptography for speed, and public-key cryptography for ease of secure key exchange, typically by using the recipient's public key to encrypt a session key which is used only once.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] This mode of operation is part of the OpenPGP standard and has been part of PGP from its first version.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The GnuPG 1.x series uses an integrated cryptographic library, while the GnuPG 2.x series replaces this with Libgcrypt.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG encrypts messages using asymmetric key pairs individually generated by GnuPG users.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The resulting public keys may be exchanged with other users in a variety of ways, such as Internet key servers.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] They must always be exchanged carefully to prevent identity spoofing by corrupting public key ↔ "owner" identity correspondences.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] It is also possible to add a cryptographic digital signature to a message, so the message integrity and sender can be verified, if a particular correspondence relied upon has not been corrupted.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG also supports symmetric encryption algorithms.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] By default, GnuPG uses the AES symmetrical algorithm since version 2.1, CAST5 was used in earlier versions.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG does not use patented or otherwise restricted software or algorithms.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Instead, GnuPG uses a variety of other, non-patented algorithms.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] For a long time, it did not support the IDEA encryption algorithm used in PGP.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] It was in fact possible to use IDEA in GnuPG by downloading a plugin for it, however, this might require a license for some uses in countries in which IDEA was patented.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Starting with versions 1.4.13 and 2.0.20, GnuPG supports IDEA because the last patent of IDEA expired in 2012.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Support of IDEA is intended "to get rid of all the questions from folks either trying to decrypt old data or migrating keys from PGP to GnuPG", and hence is not recommended for regular use.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG was initially developed by Werner Koch.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The first production version, version 1.0.0, was released on September 7, 1999, almost two years after the first GnuPG release (version 0.0.0).
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The German Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology funded the documentation and the port to Microsoft Windows in 2000.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GnuPG is a system compliant to the OpenPGP standard, thus the history of OpenPGP is of importance; it was designed to interoperate with PGP, an email encryption program initially designed and developed by Phil Zimmermann.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] On February 7, 2014, a GnuPG crowdfunding effort closed, raising €36,732 for a new website and infrastructure improvements.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Different GnuPG 2.x versions (e.g. from the 2.2 and 2.0 branches) cannot be installed at the same time.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] However, it is possible to install a "classic" GnuPG version (i.e. from the 1.4 branch) along with any GnuPG 2.x version.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Before the release of GnuPG 2.2 ("modern"), the now deprecated "stable" branch (2.0) was recommended for general use, initially released on November 13, 2006.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] This branch reached its end-of-life on December 31, 2017; Its last version is 2.0.31, released on December 29, 2017.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Before the release of GnuPG 2.0, all stable releases originated from a single branch; i.e., before November 13, 2006, no multiple release branches were maintained in parallel.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] (Note that before the release of GnuPG 2.3.0, branches with an odd minor release number (e.g.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] 2.1, 1.9, 1.3) were development branches leading to a stable release branch with a "+ 0.1" higher version number (e.g.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] 2.2, 2.0, 1.4); hence branches 2.2 and 2.1 both belong to the "modern" series, 2.0 and 1.9 both to the "stable" series, while the branches 1.4 and 1.3 both belong to the "classic" series.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] With the release of GnuPG 2.3.0, this nomenclature was altered to be composed of a "stable" and "LTS" branch from the "modern" series, plus 1.4 as the last maintained "classic" branch.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Although the basic GnuPG program has a command-line interface, there exists various front-ends that provide it with a graphical user interface.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] For example, GnuPG encryption support has been integrated into KMail and Evolution, the graphical email clients found in KDE and GNOME, the most popular Linux desktops.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] There are also graphical GnuPG front-ends, for example Seahorse for GNOME and KGPG and Kleopatra for KDE.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GPGTools provides a number of front-ends for OS integration of encryption and key management as well as GnuPG installations via Installer packages for macOS.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] GPG Suite installs all related OpenPGP applications (GPG Keychain), plugins (GPG Mail) and dependencies (MacGPG), along with GPG Services (integration into macOS Services menu) to use GnuPG based encryption.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Instant messaging applications such as Psi and Fire can automatically secure messages when GnuPG is installed and configured.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Web-based software such as Horde also makes use of it.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The cross-platform extension Enigmail provides GnuPG support for Mozilla Thunderbird and SeaMonkey.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Similarly, Enigform provides GnuPG support for Mozilla Firefox.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In 2005, g10 Code GmbH and Intevation GmbH released Gpg4win, a software suite that includes GnuPG for Windows, GNU Privacy Assistant, and GnuPG plug-ins for Windows Explorer and Outlook.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] These tools are wrapped in a standard Windows installer, making it easier for GnuPG to be installed and used on Windows systems.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The OpenPGP standard specifies several methods of digitally signing messages.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In 2003, due to an error in a change to GnuPG intended to make one of those methods more efficient, a security vulnerability was introduced.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] It affected only one method of digitally signing messages, only for some releases of GnuPG (1.0.2 through 1.2.3), and there were fewer than 1000 such keys listed on the key servers.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Most people did not use this method, and were in any case discouraged from doing so, so the damage caused (if any, since none has been publicly reported) would appear to have been minimal.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Support for this method has been removed from GnuPG versions released after this discovery (1.2.4 and later).
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In both cases updated versions of GnuPG were made available at the time of the announcement.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In June 2017, a vulnerability (CVE-2017-7526) was discovered within Libgcrypt by Bernstein, Breitner and others: a library used by GnuPG, which enabled a full key recovery for RSA-1024 and about more than 1/8 of RSA-2048 keys.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] This side-channel attack exploits the fact that Libgcrypt used a sliding windows method for exponentiation which leads to the leakage of exponent bits and to full key recovery.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Again, an updated version of GnuPG was made available at the time of the announcement.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] Around June 2018, the SigSpoof attacks were announced.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] These allowed an attacker to convincingly spoof digital signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In January 2021, Libgcrypt 1.9.0 was released, which was found to contain a severe bug that was simple to exploit.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] A fix was released 10 days later in Libgcrypt 1.9.1.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In December 2025, at Chaos Communication Congress, Lexi Groves (aka 49016) and Liam Wachter presented a series of vulnerabilities in GnuPG, ranging from remote code execution to unauthorized subkey addition.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The team reported those bugs to the GnuPG issue tracker, with some of them getting fixed and others still remaining unresolved.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] In November 2023, the LibrePGP standard was released.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] This was in response to changes made to the OpenPGP standard that were perceived by the GnuPG team to be unfounded.
[src:artifact-signing/gnu-privacy-guard] The GnuPG project no longer aims to comply with the OpenPGP standard, instead opting to comply with their own LibrePGP standard, which is meant to be based on the OpenPGP standard as it existed in November 2007.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:artifact-signing/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
